:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Peverell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Peverall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peverall","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Old French  <i>Peurel</i> (Latin  <i>Piperellus</i>), a diminutive of Old French  <i>pevre</i> ‘pepper’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>peivere</i>, Latin  <i>piper</i>), originally perhaps used as a nickname on the Continent but used as a personal name in Anglo-Norman England."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Peverell V was born in 1380, in Dorset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Andrew de Peverell II, was 20 and his mother, Mrs. Andrew De Peverell, was 15. He married Ann Margaret Courtenay in 1409, in Bradford, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1442, in 